1. What inspired you to create this app?

What inspired me to create EcoQuest Wildfire Watch was seeing how wildfires have become such a serious problem in California and the West Coast. Every summer, it feels like the skies turn orange somewhere nearby, and people have to evacuate their homes. I’ve always been interested in the environment, especially through my experience in Boy Scouts, where we spend a lot of time outdoors learning about nature, fire safety, and survival skills. Seeing how fire can both help and harm ecosystems made me realize how important it is to understand wildfire risk before it’s too late. One day during a camping trip, our troop had to cancel a hike because of poor air quality from a nearby wildfire. That really stuck with me. It made me think about how unpredictable wildfires are and how little most people know about their own risk. I wanted to build something that could help communities be more aware and prepared, even if they don’t live right next to a forest. That’s when the idea for my app came to me. EcoQuest Wildfire Watch lets users enter their location and instantly see their wildfire risk level, along with useful tips about staying safe and protecting their surroundings. I wanted it to be simple enough for anyone to use but powerful enough to make a difference. My goal was to combine my interest in technology with my passion for the outdoors to create something that helps people and the environment. Developing the app taught me how technology can be a tool for environmental protection. By giving people information about their wildfire risk, it encourages awareness and prevention, which are key to reducing damage. Creating this app made me feel like I was taking action, not just learning about problems but actually doing something to help solve them.

